# LLM Documentation Rules

These rules apply to all AI/LLM-specific documentation in the `llm-docs/` directory.

## Documentation Updates
- Keep `architecture.mdx` updated when making structural changes
- Document all new integration points
- Update documentation when adding new features
- Maintain version history of significant changes

## AI-Friendly Documentation Style
- Use clear, explicit language
- Provide concrete examples
- Include context for decisions
- Document edge cases and limitations

## Examples
- Include clear examples for common operations
```typescript
// Example: Adding a new blog post
const newPost = {
  title: "Post Title",
  description: "Description here",
  date: "2024-03-01",
  // ... other required fields
};

// Example: Using Chakra UI responsive design
const responsiveComponent = {
  width: { base: "100%", md: "50%" },
  padding: [2, 4, 6],
};
```

## Debugging Guidelines
- Update debugging tips when new issues are discovered
- Document common error scenarios
- Provide troubleshooting steps
- Include relevant log examples

## Performance Documentation
- Document performance implications of changes
- Include benchmark results when relevant
- Document optimization strategies
- Monitor and update performance metrics

## Security Considerations
- Keep security documentation current
- Document security best practices
- Update security protocols
- Document security incident responses

## Integration Documentation
- Document all external service integrations
- Keep API documentation current
- Document authentication flows
- Update integration troubleshooting guides

## Maintenance
- Review documentation quarterly
- Update outdated information
- Remove deprecated content
- Keep examples current with latest practices